Section 1

Descriptive statistics

Explain which types of descriptive summary statistic and visualization are most appropriate for each type of statistical measure

There are 3 types of descriptive summary statistic. They are measure of frequency, measure of central tendency and measure of dispersion/variation.

Frequency can be be measured either using count or using percentage.

EXAMPLE: Let us assume that the variable of interest is whether a person lives in urban area or rural area. The outcome of the variable would be urban or rural. In such cases, we can report frequency and percentage as a measure.

Central tendency is appropriate to describe numerical data. This is representative value around which all the numbers in the set tend to cluster. There are three measures to describe the central tendency. They are mode, median, and mean.

Mode is the value that occurs most frequently for a variable in a set of data. This is not a good measure when there is same frequency for all unique elements in the set. A set can have multiple modes when more than one element has the highest frequency.

Median is middle value of a sequence of all the values in a distribution arranged from lowest to highest when the set has odd number of elements. In case, the set has even number of elements, the median is the average of the middle two elements after they are arranged in an ascending order.

Mean is arithmetic average of a group of values.

Dispersion/Variability is used to measure how the values of a variable are spread. This helps us identify whether all the values of a variable are clustered close together. Usual and unusual values can be identified using measure of variability.

Range is simplest numeric measure of variability. This can be used when a variable has upper threshold or lower threshold(or both) that should not be crossed. For example, age of a person, born month of a person etc.

Variance is used to measure how the data is deviated from the mean. This can be calculated as average of the squares of the differences from the mean.

Standard deviation is square root of the variance. This value is always greater than zero. Only if all the elements are same then the standard deviation is zero.

Interquartile range is the range of the middle half of the data. It allows to understand the distribution of values within the set.

EXAMPLE: Consider a set that indicates age of all the players of the cricket team.

Age: 23, 28, 23, 24, 23, 26, 24, 21, 23, 25, 27

Mode : The mode is the number that is repeated more often than any other, hence, 23 is the mode.

Median : 21, 23, 23, 23, 23, 24, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28

The dataset has 11 numbers. (11+1)/2 i.e.6th number is median i.e.24 Mean: (21+ 23+ 23+23+ 23+ 24+ 24+ 25+ 26+ 27+ 28) / 11 = 24.27

Mean of the age is 24.27

Range of the variable age is 21-28

Variance is 4.22. It is computed by subtracting every observation with mean and taking the square of it. All the values are summed up and the final total is divided by divided by degrees of freedom.

Standard deviation is 2.05. This is squareroot of the variance.

x<-c(23, 28, 23, 24, 23, 26, 24, 21, 23, 25, 27)

meanX <- mean(x)
cat("Mean is",round(meanX,2),"\n")
## Mean is 24.27
getMode <- function(v) {
   uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}  #ref: https://www.tutorialspoint.com/r/r_mean_median_mode.htm

modeX <- getMode(x)
cat("Mode is",modeX,"\n")
## Mode is 23
medianX <- median(x)
cat("Median is",medianX,"\n")
## Median is 24
cat("Range is",range(x),"\n")
## Range is 21 28
cat("Variance is",round(var(x),2),"\n")
## Variance is 4.22
cat("Standard deviation is",round(sd(x),2),"\n")
## Standard deviation is 2.05


Appropriate graph for statistic:
Interval/Ratio (normally distributed) - Mean & std deviation - Histogram

Interval/Ratio (skewed/kurtosis) - Median & IQR - Histogram / Box plot

Nominal/Ordinal data - Mode & simple frequencies - Bar charts / Pie charts / Frequency tables.

Section 2

Assessing a variable for normality

To understand about the distribution the variable is following, as a analyst we need to follow following steps.
  • Inspect the data
  • Generate descriptive statistics
  • Generate visuals
  • Make decision about normality
The following graphs help to assess a variable for normality.
  • Histogram
  • QQ plot
  • Boxplot (helps to identify skewness and kurtosis)

Histogram is a graphical display of distribution of a numeric variable. Horizontal axis represents possible values of the variable. Vertical axis represents frequency or relative frequency. Horizontal axis can be divided into smaller chunks and are called as bins. These bins can be used to represent continuous values. If the graph is bell-shaped, single peaked and symmetrical around the centre we can conclude that graph is normally distributed. We can draw density curve over histogram to understand overall pattern of a distribution. A distribution is normal if its density curve is symmetric, single peaked and bell shaped.


QQ plot is a scatter plot created by plotting two sets of quantiles against one another. If both sets of quantiles come from the same distribution, the points roughly form a straight line.


Boxplot is a graphical display that describes the properties of a numeric variable using quartiles. This plot is usually used when we need to compare multiple numerical variables and need to point out at the outliers. In case of normal distribution, the box will be symmetrical with the mean and median in the center with some outliers. Skewness can be clearly identified when the graph is shrink towards either upper half or lower half. Wider spread of box means data is kurtosis.


Usually, a standard normal distribution has mean 0 and standard deviation 1. Histogram makes use of measure of central tendency (mean and median) to describe the normality of the data. Density curves that are bell-shaped, single peaked and symmetrical around the centre are said to follow normal distribution.

When it is difficult to assess the variable for normality using histogram and QQ-plot, standardized scores for skewness value between +/-2 are considered for acceptable in order to prove normal univariate distribution. When the values does not fall in the standard acceptance range of skewness, we can check the impact of outliers. At 0.05 level if 95% of data is within +/- 1.96 when converted to standardized scores it is safe to treat data as normal. When the sample size is small (80 or less cases), a standard score of +/- 2.58 can be considered for outlier. When the sample size is large (more than 80 observations), a case is an outlier if its standard score is +/-3.29 or beyond.

Tests such as Shapiro-Wilks / Kolmogrov-Smirnoff can be used to check the normal distribution of the variable. Larger sample requires analysis of histograms with fitted normal curves, QQ-plots and skewness and kurtosis values.

Section 3

Type I and Type II errors

When probability based conclusion is made to accept/reject null hypothesis there are four different possibilities of doing the same.

CASE I:
Nature of null hypothesis is true and statistical test also said that the fact is true.
CASE II:
Nature of null hypothesis is false and statistical test concluded that the fact is false.
CASE III:
Nature of null hypothesis is true whereas statistical test concluded that the fact is false.
CASE IV:
Nature of null hypothesis is false whereas statistical test concluded that the fact is true.

Last two cases mentioned does lead to errors as the conclusion drawn from the statistical test is is opposite than the nature of the null hypothesis. These two scenarios are known as Type I and Type II errors.

Type I error is the case of false positive, when a researcher incorrectly rejects the true null hypothesis. Type II error is the case of false negative, when a researcher incorrectly accepts the false null hypothesis.

Researcher can lower the chances of rejecting null hypothesis (type I error) when the fact is naturally true by reducing the value of p.However, this may increase the chances of accepting a null hypothesis which is not true by nature(type II errors).

For example, let us consider the null hypothesis which states that the Earth revolves around the sun. Alternate hypothesis would be Earth does not revolve around the sun. If researcher concludes to reject null hypothesis after conducting the statistical test, then it leads to Type I error as the null hypothesis is true and the alternate hypothesis is false.

As another example for Type II error, consider the null hypothesis Dogs sweat by salivating. Alternate hypothesis would be Dogs dont sweat by salivating. If researcher concludes to accept the null hypothesis after conducting the statistical test, then it leads to Type II error as the null hypothesis is false. #ref : https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2996198/

Section 4

Statistical power and statistical signifincance

Statistical power, or the power of a hypothesis test is the probability that the test correctly rejects the null hypothesis i.e.true positive cases. This has relevance when the null hypothesis is false. The statistical power ranges from 0 to 1. Higher the value of statistical power lower the value of making type II error.

The significance level, is a measure of the strength of the evidence that must be present in sample before rejecting the null hypothesis. Usually, significance level is determined before conducting experiment. This significance value is compared to p-value, if the p-value is less than significance level, one can reject the null hypothesis by concluding the effect is statistically significant.

Statistical power, significance level, sample size and effect size are all related to each other. Statistical power gives the probability of accepting alternate hypothesis when it is true. Significance level is used in the statistical test that is used to compare with the probability value either to accept or reject the null hypothesis. Generally, 0.05 is considered as significance level. This is indicated by symbol alpha. Sample size represents total number of observations that are chosen from the entire sample. Effect size measures the strength of the relationship between two variables. This can computed by statistical measure such as Pearsons correlation for the relationship between variables or Cohens d for the difference between groups.

Section 5

Correlation

Correlation describes the relationship between two variables. When the data is plotted using scatter plot, it is possible to understand whether data has positive/negative relationship ; strong/weak relationship.

Positive relationship means both variables are moving in the upward direction. EXAMPLE: Height and weight are positively correlated. One increases other variable should also increase.

Negative relationship means value of one variable increases and other descreses.

EXAMPLE: Number of hours spent on playing video games and GPA scored in the semester exam are negatively correlated.

Strong correlation means all the values from the set falls on a linear line, whereas in weak relationship datapoints are scattered around the linear line and distance between the value and linear line is high.

Steps involved in conducting a correlation test:
  1. Define a null and alternative hypothesis.
  2. Draw a scatterplot by considering independent variable on horizontal axis and dependent variables on vertical axis.
  3. Plot each point that corresponds to the observations.
  4. Conduct correlation test by inspecting normality of the data.
  5. Accept/Reject null hypothesis and mention the relationship between variables(strong/weak ; positive/negative).
Test used for normally distributed and non-normally distributed data:
  1. Normally distributed data:

    2. Pearson correlation is used when data is normally distributed. There are two other factors that need to be considered before using this test i.e.linearity and homoscedasticity. Linearity means there must be a linear relationship between the variables that we are interested in to identify the correlation. Homoscedasticity represents equal distribution of data across the regression line. Data: Interval or Ratio

  2. Non-normally distributed data:

    3. Spearman or Kendall correlation test is used to when data does not follow any distribution. However, this test requires a monotonic relationship between the variables and ordering of data must be possible. Data: Ordinal

    Reporting findings:

    The following factors need to be reported:
    1. Variables on which the test is conducted
    2. Type of test conducted
    3. Effect of relation (Strong/weak and positive/negative)
    4. p - value ; number of samples and r value for Pearson / for Spearman / tau for Kendall
    5. Total number of observations (n-2)

      6. Reporting Pearson correlation:

      r(n) = the r statistic, p = p value.

      r represents how strong the correlation is. p value is used to check whether to accept the null hypothesis or reject. n represents number of freedom (total datapoints - 2).

      Along with r and p value, strength of the relationship between variables also need to reported. Variables are positively correlated if the magnitude of r statistic is positive; negatively correlated if the magnitude of r statistic is negative. Zero indicates there is no correlation between variables.

      Reporting Spearman or Kendall correlation:

      i.e.Spearmans rho is used to describe finding of Spearman correlation. Kendalls tau is used to describe the finding of Kendall correlation.

      p value >= r ; no evidence to reject the null hypothesis. p value < r ; have evidence to reject null hypothesis in favour of the alternate hypothesis.

      EXAMPLE:

      1. When there is no correlation:
        2. The relationship between age and final grade was investigated using a Kendall correlation. No significant correlation was found (tau =0.23, n=380, p=0.82). There is therefore no evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between students age and their final grade.
      2. When there is a correlation:
        3. The relationship between travel time and grade scored in test 2 was investigated using a Pearson correlation. A weak negative correlation was found (r =-0.19, n=380, p=0.0002).

      The above mentioned statistical measures gives the association between variables. Some other statistical measures exists that compares mean of differences between two groups.

Section 6

Difference

Difference is another approach of experiment to compare two or more groups. The experiments compares means or scores of each group. Such experiments will help in understanding behavioral changes in the group that we are interested in. Statistical test helps to understand the difference is two groups have occurred naturally or by chance.

For example, let us consider two different organizations have announced vaccine for COVID-19, to compare whose vaccine is more effective we can make use of statistical test by having 2 group of people and observe the differences between the two groups.

Conducting statistical test involves declaring hypothesis. Common universally accepted fact is declared as null hypothesis. The fact which is mutually exclusive to the null hypothesis is declared as alternate hypothesis. Variables of interest are tested for normality, based on the type of distribution tests are selected. Parametric tests are selected if the sample is normally distributed. All other cases non parametric tests are considered.

Tests are chosen based on the type of independent variable and dependent variable. When the data is normally distributed we can choose the tests among t-test and ANOVA. If independent variable has two categories t-test can be selected whereas for more than two categories ANOVA can be selected. When the data is not normally distributed we can choose the tests among Kruskal and Mann-whitney. Mann-whitney test is chosen when independent variable is binary categorical, more than 2 categories Kruskal test is selected. Tests vary if the same observations are considered at different time point for the experiment.

While reporting the analysis of the difference test the following things need to be considered:
  1. To compare two groups:
    1. Normally distributed data: The report content includes
      • Type of test
      • Variables of interest and group
      • Significance of the test with mean and standard deviation of each group
      • Degrees of freedom with t statistic and p value
      • Effect size of Cohens d test and ETA squared test
    2. Not normally distributed: The report content includes
      • Type of test
      • Variables of interest
      • Significance of the test with median of each group
      • Statistical U value and p value
  2. To compare more than two groups:
    1. Normally distributed data: The report contents includes
      • Type of the test
      • Variables of interest
      • Number of groups
      • Statistical significance with mean, standard deviation of each group
      • If the test is statistically significance, F-score, p value and degrees of freedom needs to be reported.
      • If the test is statistically significance, posthoc tests need to be reported.
    2. Not normally distributed: The report contents include
      • Type of test
      • Variables of interest
      • Chi-square value and p value
      • Mean rank of each group

4. Identify at least one difference effect involving a concept of interest and involving two groups you want to investigate

H0 : There is no difference in second period grade for students who do not have family support and those who have family support.
H1 : There is a difference in second period grade for students who have do family support and those who have family support.

We know that pG2 (i.e.scores achieved in exam 2) is normally distributed. #Difference in between 2 groups

#Get descriptive statistics by group 
psych::describeBy(student$pG2, group=student$famsup.p,mat=TRUE)
##     item group1 vars   n     mean       sd median trimmed    mad min max range
## X11    1     no    1 143 12.06294 2.614200     12 12.0000 2.9652   7  18    11
## X12    2    yes    1 239 12.34310 2.376236     12 12.2487 1.4826   5  19    14
##          skew    kurtosis        se
## X11 0.2042200 -0.54913016 0.2186103
## X12 0.2891146  0.01720574 0.1537059

Along with normally distributed data, variance of these populations should have roughly equal variance. This can be tested using levenes test. The p-value is under 0.05 means that variances are not equal and further parametric tests are not suitable.

#Conduct Levene's test for homogeneity of variance in library car - the null hypothesis is that variances in groups are equal so to assume homogeneity we woudl expect probaility to not be statistically significant.
car::leveneTest(pG2 ~ famsup.p, data=student)
## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value Pr(>F)
## group   1  2.0655 0.1515
##       380
#Conduct the t-test from package stats
#In this case we can use the var.equal = TRUE option to specify equal variances and a pooled variance estimate
stats::t.test(pG2 ~ famsup.p, equal=TRUE,data=student)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  pG2 by famsup.p
## t = -1.0484, df = 276.75, p-value = 0.2954
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8062361  0.2459177
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          12.06294          12.34310
#No statistically significant difference was found

res <- stats::t.test(pG2 ~ famsup.p, var.equal=TRUE,data=student)
#Calculate Cohen's d
#artithmetically
effcd=round((2*res$statistic)/sqrt(res$parameter),2)

#Using function from effectsize package
effectsize::t_to_d(t = res$statistic, res$parameter)
##     d |        95% CI
## ---------------------
## -0.11 | [-0.31, 0.09]
#Eta squared calculation
effes=round((res$statistic*res$statistic)/((res$statistic*res$statistic)+(res$parameter)),3)
effes
##     t 
## 0.003

Negative t-test value indicates that the second subgroup mean is larger than the first subgroup mean.

Reporting the results with Cohens d effect

An independent-samples t-test was conducted to compare grade obtained in test 2 for students who have family support and those who do not have family support. No significant difference in the scores for grade obtained was found (M=12.06, SD= 2.61 for respondents who do not have family support, M= 12.34, SD= 2.38 for students who have family support), (t(382)= -1.05, p = 0.29). Cohens d also indicated a very small effect size (-0.11).

Effect size is negative indicates mean of the group who have family support is larger than mean of the group who do not have family support.

Reporting the results with eta squred effect

An independent-samples t-test was conducted to compare grade obtained in test 2 for students who have family support and those who do not have family support. No significant difference in the scores for grade obtained was found (M=12.06, SD= 2.61 for respondents who do not have family support, M= 12.34, SD= 2.38 for students who have family support), (t(382)= -1.05, p = 0.29). A very small effect size was also indicated by the eta squared value (0.003).

Reporting An one-way between-groups analysis of variance (ANOVA) was conducted to to explore the studytime and second period grade. Participants were divided into four groups according number of hours they dedicate to study (Group 1: < 2 hours ; Group 2: 2-5 hours ; Group 3: 5-10 hours ; Group 4: > 10 hours). There was a statistically significant difference at the p < .05 level in second period grade for the four different studytime groups: (F(2,380) = 32.25, p<.05). Despite reaching statistical significance, the actual difference in the mean scores between groups was quite small. The effect size, calculated using eta squared was (0.08). Post-hoc comparisons using the Tukey HSD test indicated that the mean score for Group 1 (M=11.24, SD =2.44) was significantly different from Group 2 (M=12.25, SD=2.31) and Group 3(M=13.46, SD=1.15). Group 2 did not differ significantly from Group 4 (M=13.04, SD=2.83).

H0: There are no differences between second period grade and family relationship for students in Group 1, Group 2, Group 3, Group 4 or Group 5. H1: There are differences between second period grade and family relationship for students in Group 1, Group 2, Group 3, Group 4 or Group 5.
